m Middle English <i>squyer</i>, <i>squer</i>, <i>skier</i>, <i>sker</i>, northern Middle English <i>swire</i> (Old French <i>escuyer</i>, <i>escuier</i>) ‘shield bearer, esquire, personal attendant to a knight; landowner below the rank of knight; young man of gentle birth; household attendant, retainer, page, messenger’. Many early bearers of this name were of modest means and cannot have been members of the gentry; in such cases the name may have been used hyperbolically for a low-ranking servant or as a nickname. By the 17th century, the term denoted any member of the landed gentry, but this is unlikely to have influenced the development of the surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Swire","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Squire  , from a northern form of the word."]},{"name":"Quire","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Squire  .","Scottish or Irish: shortened form of   McQuire   (see   McGuire  )."]},{"name":"Squires","meanings":["English: variant of   Squire  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Scuderi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmelo, Salvatore, Angelo, Carlo, Gaetano, Vito, Antonio, Dante, Mario, Rocco, Rosario, Antonino, Biaggio, Eduardo, Ermelinda, Margarita.","Italian (Sicily): status name equivalent to   Squire  , from <i>scudiero</i>, <i>scutiero</i>, dialect <i>scuteri</i> ‘shieldbearer’ (from medieval Latin <i>scutarius</i>, an agent derivative of <i>scutum</i> ‘shield’). In Byzantium, the Greek word <i>skoutarios</i> denoted a member of the imperial guard."]},{"name":"Square","meanings":["English (Devon) and Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Squire  ."]},{"name":"Squier","meanings":["English: variant of   Squire  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Squyre was born about 1430, in Romsley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas Deol Squyre. He had at least 2 sons with Deol Squire. He died about 1505, in his hometown, at the age of 77."},"et":{"Abt 1430–Abt 1505":"umbes 1430–umbes 1505","1430–1505":"1430–1505","1435–1458":"1435–1458","1450–1481":"1450–1481","1458–1528":"1458–1528","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1456":"1456","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1481":"1481","Abt 1505":"umbes 1505","1528":"1528","1505":"1505","Romsley, Worcestershire, England":"Romsley, Worcestershire, England","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Romsley, Shropshire, England":"Romsley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benwick, Cambridgeshire, England":"Benwick, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1430–Abt 1505":"noin 1430–noin 1505","1430–1505":"1430–1505","1435–1458":"1435–1458","1450–1481":"1450–1481","1458–1528":"1458–1528","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1456":"1456","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"noin 1430","1430":"1430","1450":"1450","1481":"1481","Abt 1505":"noin 1505","1528":"1528","1505":"1505","Romsley, Worcestershire, England":"Romsley, Worcestershire, England","Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Romsley, Shropshire, England":"Romsley, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Benwick, Cambridgeshire, England":"Benwick, Cambridgeshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1430–Abt 1505":"environ 1430–environ 1505","1430–1505":"1430–1505","1435–1458":"1435–1458"